{"cursor":"6614","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematics, a 'directed set' (or a 'directed preorder' or a 'filtered set')\nis a nonempty set A together with a reflexive and transitive binary relation â¤\n(that is, a preorder), with the additional property that every pair of elements\nhas an upper bound: Kelley, p. 65. In other words, for any a and b in\nA there must exist a c in A with a â¤ c and b â¤ c.\n\nDirected sets are a generalization of nonempty totally ordered sets, that is,\nall totally ordered sets are directed sets (contrast ''partially'' ordered sets\nwhich need not be directed). In topology, directed sets are used to define nets,\nwhich generalize sequences and unite the various notions of limit used in\nanalysis. Directed sets also give rise to direct limits in abstract algebra and\n(more generally) category theory.\n","linknr":143,"url":"Directed_set","recorded":1362372615,"links":20,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","order_theory","topology","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Mathematical relations","Order theory","General topology"],"headings":["Equivalent definition","Examples","Contrast with semilattices","Directed subsets","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/e/e/9eedd61e32f7a8e70e171028a7e5dc08.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/e/e/9eedd61e32f7a8e70e171028a7e5dc08.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e78f632038354aae583f795a73d4e6b8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e78f632038354aae583f795a73d4e6b8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e78f632038354aae583f795a73d4e6b8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e78f632038354aae583f795a73d4e6b8.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["set","mathematics"],["net","topology"],["limit","mathematics"],["ideal","order_theory"]